Does T4G Theory Permit &ldquo;Free Will&rdquo;? Short answer is a qualified, &ldquo;Yes it does.&rdquo;
Long answer is that it depends on what you mean by &ldquo;free will.

What Emerges? It is very trendy these days to adopt the holographic conception of physics and claim that the fundamental reality is a field theory on the boundary, and that spacetime in the bulk is &ldquo;emergent&rdquo;. But what does this mean?
Given the dual descriptions are equivalences, it means nothing truly &ldquo;emerges.&rdquo;
However, physicists have a hard time thinking about how quantum mechanics can have anything to do with spacetime as described in general relativity, so they tend to want to regard entanglement and other &ldquo;quantum&rdquo; phenomena as more fundamental than the spacetime.

The easy way This is a short post on &ldquo;why complex amplitudes?&rdquo;
I&rsquo;ll refer you to Scott Aaronson&rsquo;s blog, Shetl Optimized. The idea here is that we have little option but to employ complex numbers for the QM amplitudes. No other algebraic field works.
In other words, the &ldquo;proof&rdquo; that T4G theory implies geometric amplitudes could be as simple as verifying the logic is the same as quantum logic, so no nasty dynamical theory proof or derivation may be needed (although it&rsquo;d also be desirable at some point).
